    "body" : "<ol>\n<li>You should add <code>L</code>: <code>long i = 12345678910L;</code>.</li>\n<li>Yes.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>BTW: it doesn't have to be an upper case L, but lower case is confused with <code>1</code> many times :).</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 183607,
      "reputation" : 34242,
      "user_id" : 419075,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 96,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/90b33a04a2ccc63534d1d9f4aac1fb7a?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Amir Raminfar",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/419075/amir-raminfar"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 43,
    "last_activity_date" : 1311701374,
    "creation_date" : 1311701374,
    "answer_id" : 6834054,
    "question_id" : 6834037,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>You need to add uppercase <code>L</code> at the end like so</p>\n\n<pre><code>long i = 12345678910L;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Same goes true for float with <code>3.0f</code></p>\n\n<p>Which should answer both of your questions </p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 24285,
      "reputation" : 33481,
      "user_id" : 61663,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 92,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/6db1199d54134a53b101dcc3850fda57?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Jack Edmonds",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/61663/jack-edmonds"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 72,
    "last_activity_date" : 1311701534,
    "creation_date" : 1311701534,
    "answer_id" : 6834080,
    "question_id" : 6834037,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<ol>\n<li><p>You need to add the <code>L</code> character to the end of the number to make Java recognize it as a long.</p>\n\n<pre><code>long i = 12345678910L;\n</code></pre></li>\n<li><p>Yes.</p></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>See <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/nutsandbolts/datatypes.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Primitive Data Types</a> which says \"An integer literal is of type long if it ends with the letter L or l; otherwise it is of type int.\"</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2980512,
      "reputation" : 536,
      "user_id" : 2802705,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/O0dWI.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Suraj Dubey",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2802705/suraj-dubey"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 20,
    "last_activity_date" : 1490048932,
    "last_edit_date" : 1490048932,
    "creation_date" : 1401685645,
    "answer_id" : 23987644,
    "question_id" : 6834037,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>To initialize long you need to append \"L\" to the end. <br>\nIt can be either uppercase or lowercase. <br></p>\n\n<p>All the numeric values are by default <code>int</code>. Even when you do any operation of <code>byte</code> with any integer, <code>byte</code> is first promoted to <code>int</code> and then any operations are performed. <br></p>\n\n<p>Try this</p>\n\n<pre><code>byte a = 1; // declare a byte\na = a*2; //  you will get error here\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>You get error because <code>2</code> is by default <code>int</code>. <br>\nHence you are trying to multiply <code>byte</code> with <code>int</code>.\nHence result gets typecasted to <code>int</code> which can't be assigned back to <code>byte</code>.</p>\n"
  } ],
